<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,994,1019]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Description.</emphasis>
Measurements (in mm) and ratios: BL 2.50; FL 1.72; HL 0.41; HW 0.53; PL 0.53; PW 0.60; EL 1.13; EW 1.29; HL/HW 0.77; PL/PW 0.88; EL/EW 0.88; PL/EL 0.82; AnL 1.38; AeL 0.50.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[351,454,1066,1091]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1471,1493]" captionTargetBox="[221,1413,238,1457]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[168,1415,226,1460]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 16. Habitus (males) of Lesteva: A—L. obesa sp. nov.; B—L. ochra. Scale bar: 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2627288/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 16A</figureCitation>
. Reddish brown, head usually darker, blackish brown; mouthparts and antennae fuscous brown; elytra reddish brown, but lateral and posterior margin paler; elytra with obscure oblique dark red maculae, extending from shoulders toward suture in middle of the elytra; femora fuscous brown, tibiae paler, tarsi yellowish brown. Pubescence of body pale, evident and recumbent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Head subtriangular, with very coarse and dense punctation, widest across eyes; eyes moderately large and prominent, twice as long as temples; ocelli distinct, distance between ocelli 1.22 times as long as distance between ocellus and inner margin of the compound eye. Antennae elongate, relative lengths of the antennomeres I–XI: 1.54: 1: 1: 1.08: 1.08: 1.08: 1: 1: 1: 1: 1.77.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pronotum subcordate, distinctly convex, moderately transverse widest near anterior third; lateral margins arcuate at anterior two-thirds and nearly straight at posterior third; punctation and pubescence coarser and sparser than those on head; disc with shallow U-shaped impression. Scutellum subtriangular, with fine and sparse punctation and pubescence.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Elytra subtrapezoidal, gradually dilated posteriorly, posterior angles broadly rounded; punctation and pubescence distinctly finer and sparser than those on pronotum.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Abdomen broad, widest at segment IV (first visible abdominal segment) then narrowed posteriorly; surface of tergites somewhat closely covered with very fine punctation and pubescence, without microsculpture; tergite V with a pair of large and moderately transverse tomentose patches.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Male. Apical margin of the tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[656,758,1678,1703]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[182,1417,445,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[176,1419,437,1889]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 18. Abdominal tergite VIII and sternite VIII (males, dorsal view) of Lesteva: L. obesa sp. nov. (A—abdominal tergite VIII, B—abdominal sternite VIII); L. ochra (C—abdominal tergite VIII, D—abdominal sternite VIII); L. pulcherrima (E— abdominal tergite VIII, F—abdominal sternite VIII); L. rufimarginata (G—abdominal tergite VIII, H—abdominal sternite VIII). Scale bar: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2627292/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 18A</figureCitation>
) weakly concave; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1124,1225,1678,1703]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1909,1931]" captionTargetBox="[182,1417,445,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[176,1419,437,1889]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 18. Abdominal tergite VIII and sternite VIII (males, dorsal view) of Lesteva: L. obesa sp. nov. (A—abdominal tergite VIII, B—abdominal sternite VIII); L. ochra (C—abdominal tergite VIII, D—abdominal sternite VIII); L. pulcherrima (E— abdominal tergite VIII, F—abdominal sternite VIII); L. rufimarginata (G—abdominal tergite VIII, H—abdominal sternite VIII). Scale bar: 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2627292/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 18B</figureCitation>
) transverse, apical margin strongly concave. Median lobe of the aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[780,863,1714,1739]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1985,2007]" captionTargetBox="[298,1294,199,1973]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[288,1296,193,1975]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 19. Aedeagus of Lesteva (A–C. L. obesa sp. nov. Male. D–F. L. ochra Male): A–C. Aedeagus, in dorsal (A), ventral (B) and lateral (C) view; D–F. Aedeagus, in dorsal (A), ventral (B) and lateral (C) view. Scale bar: 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2627294/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs 19</figureCitation>
A–C) significantly wide basally, narrowing toward apex, slightly longer than parameres; parameres somewhat asymmetrical, with four short apical setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" box="[199,414,1786,1811]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Female. Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,439,1822,1847]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
Based on the coloration of the body, punctation and pubescence of the head and pronotum and shape of the median lobe of the aedeagus, the new species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Rougemont" authorityName="Rougemont" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lesteva" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="qinlingmontis">
<emphasis box="[1248,1436,1858,1882]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">L. qinlingmontis</emphasis>
Rougemont
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingRegion box="[297,393,1894,1919]" country="China" name="Shaanxi" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Shaanxi</collectingRegion>
: Qinling Shan), from which it can be distinguished by a shallow U-shaped impression on the disc of the pronotum, shapes of the elytra and slender parameres. For illustrations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rougemont" authorityYear="2017" box="[1196,1386,1930,1954]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lesteva" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="qinlingmontis">
<emphasis box="[1196,1386,1930,1954]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">L. qinlingmontis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation author="Rougemont, G. - M. de" box="[151,442,1967,1991]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="101 - 111" refId="ref22555" refString="Rougemont, G. - M. de (2017) New species of Lesteva Latreille from China (Staphylinidae: Omaliinae). Entomologist`s Monthly Magazine, 153, 101 - 111." type="journal article" year="2017">Rougemont. (2017: 3, 3a)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,882,2027]" lastBlockId="19.[151,1436,151,285]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,589,2002,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Distribution and natural history.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[645,693,2003,2027]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">type</typeStatus>
locality is situated in Mt. East Dabashan to the Chengkou County, northern 
<collectingRegion box="[255,382,151,176]" country="China" name="Chongqing" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Chongqing</collectingRegion>
, near 
<collectingRegion box="[454,654,151,176]" country="China" name="Shaanxi" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Shaanxi Province</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[671,758,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 34" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1040,1062]" captionTargetBox="[164,1424,193,1012]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[164,1424,193,1019]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 34. Distribution of 24 species of Lesteva in China: 1—L. alesi, 2—L. aureomontis, 3—L. brevimacula, 4—L. cala, 5—L. chujoi, 6—L. davidiana, 7—L. elongata, 8—L. fikaceki, 9—L. flavopunctata, 10—L. hajeki, 11—L. jaechi, 12—L. lignipisces, 13—L. miragricola, 14—L. mollis, 15—L. nivalis, 16—L. obesa, 17—L. obliquonotata, 18—L. qinlingmontis, 19—L. ruficollis, 20—L. ruzickai, 21—L. schoenmanni, 22—L. smetanai, 23—L. tonitrumontis, 24—L. yunnanicola." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2627322/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
). The specimen was sifted from leaf litter near a stream in mixed deciduous forests at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[612,700,188,212]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.039" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" unit="m" value="2039.0">2039 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
